ievements they made. Coming from different cultures, environments, professions, and age groups, the authors of these essays have their own agendas and individual styles. Yet amid this diversity they deal with recurring themes that give vivid insights into what it means to be a woman in Canada in the 1990s. They write about relationships, careers, illness, children, sexuality, sexism, violence, religion, the arts, misfortune, and good luck. Monique Bégin, former minister of Health in Pierre Trudeau's cabinet, recounts her experiences in the male-dominated world of politics. Annie Iserhoff, a Cree teacher who was sent to residential schools as a child, describes her encounters with prejudice. Jane Poulson discloses the pain of going blind during her final year of medical studies and her bitter struggle to triumph over impossible odds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh1 aAbella, Rosalie Silberman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArcher, Violet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeer, Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBeer, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBégin, Monique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleather, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemers, Lise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonald, Janet G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhosh, Ratna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbs, Sarah P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIserhoff, Annie Neeposh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 